    "updated_at": "2016-08-03T14:58:47Z",
    "body": "@zcbenz You are right, it's font rendering problem: No suitable default fonts are specified.\n\nI created a new file `/etc/fonts/local.conf`, and add the following configuration:\n\n```\n<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<!DOCTYPE fontconfig SYSTEM \"fonts.dtd\">\n<fontconfig>\n<match>\n    <test name=\"family\"><string>sans-serif</string></test>\n    <edit name=\"family\" mode=\"prepend\" binding=\"strong\">\n        <string>DejaVu Sans</string>\n        <string>Microsoft Yahei</string>\n    </edit>\n</match>\n<match>\n    <test name=\"family\"><string>serif</string></test>\n    <edit name=\"family\" mode=\"prepend\" binding=\"strong\">\n        <string>Microsoft Yahei</string>\n        <string>DejaVu Serif</string>\n    </edit>\n</match>\n<match>\n    <test name=\"family\"><string>monospace</string></test>\n    <edit name=\"family\" mode=\"prepend\" binding=\"strong\">\n        <string>YaHei Consolas Hybrid</string>\n        <string>DejaVu Sans Mono</string>\n    </edit>\n</match>\n</fontconfig>\n```\n\nThe google chrome v52 or electron v1.3.1 comes back to be quite well :)\n\n![gtkshot](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1321315/17370181/ae55dcf6-59cd-11e6-8bde-ddbda49e3da4.png)\n"
  }
